<h1>How to write Mermaid diagrams in Markdown</h1>

<p>Mermaid is a JavaScript library that lets you create diagrams and charts using a simple text-based syntax inside Markdown. <a href="/documents">CodeInk</a> renders Mermaid diagrams in real-time directly in the preview pane — no plugins or external tools required.</p>

<p>To create a Mermaid diagram, use a fenced code block with <code>mermaid</code> as the language identifier:</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeBasic} />

<h2>Flowcharts</h2>

<p>Flowcharts are the most common Mermaid diagram type. They visualize processes, decision trees, and workflows. Use <code>graph TD</code> for top-down or <code>graph LR</code> for left-right direction.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeFlowchart} />

<h3>Node shapes</h3>

<ul>
  <li><code>[Text]</code> — rectangle</li>
  <li><code>(Text)</code> — rounded rectangle</li>
  <li><code>&#123;&#123;Text&#125;&#125;</code> — rhombus (diamond/decision)</li>
  <li><code>((Text))</code> — circle</li>
  <li><code>[/Text/]</code> — parallelogram</li>
  <li><code>[[Text]]</code> — subroutine</li>
</ul>

<h3>Arrow types</h3>

<ul>
  <li><code>--&gt;</code> — solid arrow</li>
  <li><code>---</code> — solid line (no arrow)</li>
  <li><code>-.-&gt;</code> — dotted arrow</li>
  <li><code>==&gt;</code> — thick arrow</li>
  <li><code>--&gt;|Label|</code> — arrow with label</li>
</ul>

<h2>Sequence diagrams</h2>

<p>Sequence diagrams show how different parts of a system interact over time. They are ideal for documenting API flows, authentication processes, and message passing.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeSequence} />

<h3>Message types</h3>

<ul>
  <li><code>-&gt;&gt;</code> — solid line with arrowhead</li>
  <li><code>--&gt;&gt;</code> — dashed line with arrowhead</li>
  <li><code>-&gt;&gt;+</code> — activate participant</li>
  <li><code>--&gt;&gt;-</code> — deactivate participant</li>
</ul>

<h2>Class diagrams</h2>

<p>Class diagrams represent the structure of object-oriented code. They show classes, their attributes, methods, and relationships.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeClass} />

<h3>Relationship types</h3>

<ul>
  <li><code>&lt;|--</code> — inheritance</li>
  <li><code>*--</code> — composition</li>
  <li><code>o--</code> — aggregation</li>
  <li><code>--&gt;</code> — association</li>
  <li><code>..&gt;</code> — dependency</li>
</ul>

<h2>Entity relationship (ER) diagrams</h2>

<p>ER diagrams are essential for database design. They show entities, their attributes, and the relationships between them.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeER} />

<h3>Relationship notation</h3>

<ul>
  <li><code>||--||</code> — one to one</li>
  <li><code>||--o&#123;</code> — one to many</li>
  <li><code>o&#123;--o&#123;</code> — many to many</li>
  <li><code>||--o|</code> — one to zero or one</li>
</ul>

<h2>Gantt charts</h2>

<p>Gantt charts are used for project planning and scheduling. They show tasks, durations, and dependencies on a timeline.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeGantt} />

<h2>Pie charts</h2>

<p>Pie charts visualize proportional data with a simple syntax.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codePie} />

<h2>State diagrams</h2>

<p>State diagrams model the behavior of a system by showing states and transitions.</p>

<CodeBlock lang="mermaid" code={codeState} />

<h2>Tips for writing Mermaid diagrams</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Start simple</strong> — begin with a few nodes and add complexity gradually.</li>
  <li><strong>Use descriptive labels</strong> — node labels should be clear and concise.</li>
  <li><strong>Choose the right direction</strong> — <code>TD</code> (top-down) works for hierarchies, <code>LR</code> (left-right) works for flows.</li>
  <li><strong>Add comments</strong> — use <code>%%</code> for comments inside Mermaid blocks.</li>
  <li><strong>Test incrementally</strong> — CodeInk renders in real-time, so you can see errors as you type.</li>
</ol>

